With this tool students will be able to learn about gear configurations and ratios of power.  
For the younger age groups, students will learn about rotation and which direction gears move as well as speed.  
Older students will learn about gear ratio and how one configuration could lead to more power in motion for later gears.  
This can also be used as a puzzle.  For example, setup one gear on one end and another at the other end, then have the students try and get one gear to spin one direction and the other one the other way with the fewest number of gears.  Students can also stack gears on top of each other, I'm hoping the gears are a snug fit to the rods, again I don't have a 3D printer so I can't test this out.  The boards themselves can also be expanded by stacking and adding rods.  The possibilities are endless :D !!

description.text:
Calibrating my z-axis on my mendel was always difficult and time consuming. Hence, I decided to add an adjustable z-axis flag holder. However, none of the things fulfilled my requirements which are: fit on standard mendel design, adjustable, should mount smoothly...
Hence I decided to create this thing...

You need 1 M4 screw
2 M4 washer
1 M4 nut
1 spring that fits on the screw and can be compressed to approx. 1cm
1 endstop - slider-holder-1
1 endstop - slider
1* endstop flag plate (I used some pcb material) instructions
1) make sure that the slider slides smoothly into the slider-holder
2) press the nut into the endstop slider
3) install the slider into the slider holder using the M4 screw, washers and spring (see figures for details)
4) mount the slider-holder on the z-axis, where the z-axis nut is mounted (see figures for details)
(---> this could be improved in future versions <---)
5) place your endstop switch accordingly
6) glue the flag plate onto the slider (always see figures for details) I mark that thing as work in progress, because its not yet perfect, the slider should be improved to integrate the endstop flag and to match a standard mendel endstop mount position). However, as it was a replacement for my mendel, I have designed it that way...

#include <AccelStepper.h>
#define HALFSTEP 8

// Motor pin definitions

#define motorPin2  4     // IN2 on the ULN2003 driver 1
#define motorPin3  5     // IN3 on the ULN2003 driver 1
#define motorPin4  6     // IN4 on the ULN2003 driver 1

AccelStepper stepper1(HALFSTEP, motorPin1, motorPin3, motorPin2, motorPin4);

description.text:
My Son wanted a Sans Mask and I liked Mizunoslove's design, but it wouldn't fit my printer...

Also it looked uncomfortable, as there is nowhere for the wearer's nose to go.

So, I cut out a void for a person's nose to fit. Then I sliced the original file into 4 pieces.

Thinking they would print smoother standing up, I rotated them.

Although the Top files would fit my WallaceG1 printer, they were too tall for my ecksbot. So, I re-sliced them to fit most 200mm bed printers.

Printer:

Echertech ecksbot

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2mm

Infill:

15

Notes:

I Printed in ABS, but PLA might work with less warping. Although glueing and possible sanding PLA may be tricky...

6 part print Step 1

Print Bottom Left and Bottom Right.

If you have a tall enough printer (>140mm) then print Top Left and Top Right.
Everyone else prints Top Left 1 & 2 and Top Right 1 & 2.

Now glue all the sections together. Some sanding may be needed. As I printed in ABS, I used Acetone on the edges to glue them together.

Sadly, the ABS warped... Step 2 or so...

I used the support pieces, some Acetone and a glass jar to make some ABS paste/slurry.

Filling More filling Step 3 ish

I used a popsicle stick to spread the paste/slurry into the gaps and along some seams.

Let it dry overnight.

Sanded paste Gaps be gone! Step done.

I sanded all the glossy and bumpy areas where the ABS paste/slurry was used, until it matched the rest of the surfaces.

Now you might want to paint.

title: Experimental Printed Base for 57mm Snap Cap

description.text:
This is a developed 3d printed model of the top end of a standard 57 mm spray can (Sure Deoderant in this case). Note the matching mating snap on cap.  The purpose of the design was to resolve some 3d printed design and sizing issues which would allow a printed base object to accept this style snap cap.  
Since there are many standard sizes for these style caps other caps of a different size and snap design will require a variant.

This particular model was designed from scratch in Solidworks 2013 and reflects only the top part of the can. The modle was then printed on an Ordbot Hadron Printer in ABS with a modified QU-BD stepstruder. It was printed using a 1.75 mm ABS filament with a layer thickness of .2 mm (200 microns) and an 85% fill factor with scaffolding support turned off.  
ABS Printing was performed at 235C on clear Monokote film over a heated glass bed at 110C for the first layer and 100C for all subsequent layers. Aquanet Extra Super Hold was sprayed on the Monokote to insure stick down. I've had no ABS stick down issues since I began using the above technique.
